At the end of the trade, the Prague stock exchange tipped into the negative.
After the fall of Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange retaliated its losses.
Transactions with the ČEZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily exchanges.
On Tuesday, from the start of trade, the Prague Stock Exchange resumed its fall the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in shares at Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the plan to stabilize the American financial sector, is thus also noticeable in our country.
Falling stocks in Asia
On Tuesday, the Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic fall, even though the clues managed, during the day, to erase some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange's Hang Seng Index lost four per cent during trade, but later it erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to almost 2.5 per cent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong stock exchange lost 3.8 per cent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney stock exchange lost more than five per cent, but ultimately losses were reduced to 4.3 per cent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 per cent.
"The hesitancy about the rescue action in the US will affect financial markets around the world," observed Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its own monetary policy, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are the same as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US legislators should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will be affected.
The bloodbath of American actions
On Monday, the American House of Representatives rejected the project to support the financial system, to which it should have spent up to $700 billion (nearly 12 billion from Kč).
Legislators thus deny the call for support for President George Bush's project.
According to Bush, the project should address the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, American stocks experienced a bloodbath and the main indices of stocks experienced the biggest fall of the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index lost almost seven percent, having fallen to such a scale for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in a free fall.
Congress gave in: US government can inject $700 billion into banks
U.S. Congress leaders and President George W. Bush's government have agreed on a broader form of the U.S. financial assistance agreement.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
The US legislators made a decisive turning point in the talks on the adoption of a rescue plan in the form of US$700 billion in financial aid (about 12 trillion crowns) granted to the US financial system.
But success is not sure.
In fact, before the Congressmans can publish the final version of the law and put it to the vote, they must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Says Sunday to Reuters Barney Frank, chair of the House's Banking and Financial Regulatory Committee.
According to sources, as early as Wednesday, the plan should a priori be put to the vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be adopted should be a major first psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
Given the complexity of the mechanisms by which market aid can be effective, however, there will be a "disillusionment".
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the form that the package of measures for market stabilisation should take," told the Bloomberg Agency, Democrat Nancy Pelosi.
According to her, the final vote could be taken on Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the legislators met with the U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson, in order to give the bottom of the government a final form.
It should buy from financial companies the unsaleable real estate assets that result in significant losses to financial companies and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective on the market.
We still need to pursue this plan to restore markets, but I think we are there," says Paulson.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a considerable impact on declining equity markets.
According to Senator Democrat Harry Reid, the legislators are doing so that Congress will reach a final agreement by Sunday.
They want to calm down investors before the start of trade in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where Congress' decision could affect Monday's trade.
However, for the time being, it is impossible to specify with certainty when the two chambers of the American Congress will vote, nor whether the negotiations are likely to remain blocked, at the last moment, by a particular problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
Nevertheless, the law will still undergo many changes.
The total amount allocated to the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the programme is not fulfilling its function, it has the possibility of blocking the remaining amount, following two steps: first, an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Bush hailed progress in negotiations
Although the president can put his veto to this decision, Congress has the opportunity to put him in a minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which consisted of obtaining finances for the purchase of bad real estate securities, whose value shook, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
U.S. President George Bush is himself pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said that Mr Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the two-party effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Limitation of golden parachutes
Chair of the Senate Banking Committee Christopher Dodd, Chief Negotiator, said that legislators agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of contributors against losses, the arrangement of discounts, the progress of the plan on the axis of time.
The new law also provides for the limitation of these golden parachutes for the directors of the companies participating in the programme and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this issue and have made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and will be effective for the market and for all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance to homeowners, who have problems to pay for.
The government should negotiate new down payments for mortgages that it will buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing debtors to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance's chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
"And this is due to the fact that we don't know what the mechanism and the price of buying out the problem assets will be.
This will be crucial in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek said this week at the iHned.cz server.
If the plan is to be adopted now, or at the beginning of next week, is, according to Marek, not as important as that.
"It is much more important that the congressmen agree, this week, that they support this plan and that they dedicate it as soon as possible.
This psychological meaning of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, is the most important at the moment," Marek stressed.
An extreme struggle: MP3 players against mobiles.
We'll advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
It seems clear from this that it is better to buy only one phone.
However, there are sufficient reasons to obtain an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a high-end expensive gramophone to put Maxim Turbulenc's new album.
On the one hand, such musical products do not come out on vinyl, and from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are piled vinyl records in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during travel, namely compressed music, to say it in a simplified way - music in MP3.
Here too, there are categories according to price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan would find it difficult to support headphones purchased for twenty crowns on the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are functions unknown, of course, to most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
Besides the primary functions, phone calls and text messages, it is able to play music and movies, record them, it has a camera of varying quality and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if you take Smartphones and communicators into account, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no fridge knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are almost witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal nature of the motive is not without its drawbacks.
The larger the number of functions you use, the smaller the interval between two reloads.
And reading music is one of the most important energy goinches.
There are few mobiles that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this respect, the music players (especially the most rudimentary ones) are significantly better performing.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you sometimes call from time to time, get, to be sure, a second reload for work - this is valid even for more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, who are able, following a reload, to continuously operate for at least 9 hours, including the least performing ones.
Another problem occurs when recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices have a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer, without a special software.
Of course, you can record music directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without any reduction, given the tiny dimensions of memory cards used in mobiles.
As far as readers are concerned, you do not need, except in iPod, any software.
Just fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and readers will create themselves a media library classified according to the interpreter's name, the title of the album, the style, or then according to the judgment of the user.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, like the Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iiver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
In the choice of a concrete device, focus on the lifetime of the accumulator, the capacity of the memory, the quality and the type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile reading MP3.
Virtually all mobiles are now capable of doing so.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to play.
All manage to play the MP3 and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have precisely this format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also read music in WMA format.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
You just have to visit the corresponding web pages of the operator (or of another supplier) from the mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason for obtaining a musical motive.
The offer of operators is unfortunately miserable and in most cases is limited to fast tube radios.
Nor are prices the lowest.
However, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, the Internet, or even the wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their motive on themselves.
Every time you want to listen to something, you just have to get the mobile out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones on you or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use built-in speakers, which have virtually all the mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical mobiles is their price.
The cheapest normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, one can have a walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the absence of an output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best equipped, also equipped with an entrance for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy command.
Really anyone manages to ensure the control of the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the least expensive (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the control to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is evident.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of a mobile internet connected by chance, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
The basic models support in principle only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive get away with even 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iiver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose specialized mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and thus the ease of control is closer to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose walkman series mobiles have the same user menu as separately sold MP3 players, is the one that went the furthest in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a lifetime of the battery (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours) higher, is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the above mentioned brands.
A first virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering almost the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we are still missing something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
He may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned, on several occasions, on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (Czech Telecommunications Office), which pointed out that the price of an SMS was higher for us than for the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the European Commission's latest steps in the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may arise - SMS messages sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, in comparison with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this regard, Pavel Dvo+k, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly stated that in Czech Republic there is no longer room for another operator, has been chorused with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with his own network is apparently no longer very lucky (more so, he would find frequencies difficult now).
However, there is still one possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable drop in prices, to which conventional operators had to react afterwards.
Yet, even before the entry of party troubles such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to those heard today at home were heard in Britain.
However, it became clear that there was room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February we informed you about the launch in Poland of the virtual operator Mobilking.
In just six months, this operator has managed to win over 100 thousand customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
Let us add that behind the Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which owns among other things the U:fon in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators being the opportunity to focus on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are, in fact, exempt from the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
Thus, in the world, virtual operators are emerging as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often counterbalanced by a limited offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers text messages in Britain that are at least twice as expensive as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity move.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"True men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work at home as well.
Miroslav Čepický, spokesman for Vodafone, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In Czech Republic, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in Czech Republic the negotiations are not very encouraging.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta Financial Group.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novela Group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of business customers, has not been hiding, for long enough, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We are keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already conducted negotiations on this possibility several times with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations," says Pavel Kaidl's spokesman.
The future may therefore be promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we might be able to host the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with other very specific ones.
For the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us," said Vlastimil Srše+ of the Telefonika O2 press department, in his statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesperson Martina Kemrová states in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally advantageous project, which could serve as a basis."
She adds: "It is virtually impossible for a virtual operator to appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited period of time, we should have a concrete agreement now."
Vodafone instead directs his attention to completing requests to obtain his own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said in relation to this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This, in our view, means the most input from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is the discovery of a partner to set up a common network for a fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in line with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would lead to lower prices and thus lower profits.
So what is the point of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to say that they are throwing away at the fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČTÚ, at the time of the creation of the U:fon, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the ČTÚ web pages.
Today, however, the U:fon lends itself to using as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted on this subject: "Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile RT market, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject him, and especially his services, to high demands."
But given the attitude of mobile operators, the indifference of Czech regulators seems disconcerting.
However, it is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
The latter belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
However, the latter adopted its typical position in the face of this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, as the offer of potential interested parties has not a priori presented sufficient interest for conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the External Relations Department of the ÚOHS.
A statement formulated in this way would not surprise representatives of operators.
But on the part of an Office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care of the fact that no one takes advantage of their position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
All the more so since Kristián Chalupa adds: "In other countries, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a drop in the prices of mobile telephone services."
However, putting pressure on the honest functioning of the market and falling prices is apparently not part of the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises quite naturally.
Similarly, a price of gasoline that is strictly identical to all service stations is probably due to the chance and hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not noted any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore none has a corresponding increased responsibility for its conduct on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably missing even from the telecom regulator," said Chaloupa.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points of discord.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position in such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different vision: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, on each occasion, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
This is how he necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of his activity.
Even without admitting this argument, it should be at least worrying for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are proceeding visibly in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including GTS Novela, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Making responsibility fall on the ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, through which the ÚOHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted Telecommunications Act has not succeeded in making the ČTÚ's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications more visible, although many specialists are promising an improvement in the situation.
This, the representatives of the ÚOHS must know very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When no one looks, it can work.
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, many in Czech mobile networks, remains undetected.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but the latter are only partially public.
In most cases, there is talk of firms involved in multi-level marketing.
Specific mobile telephone services are offered, for example, by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually reach only elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company makes in front of the operator is a classic business customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she obtains special (and other) price offers.
What is problematic is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you're talking about happened, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would be examining and that could lead to a cessation of collaboration with the company in question," answered our question about this Martina Kemrová problem.
Nevertheless, it is rather unlikely that an echo of such an activity has reached the managers of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
Ancun operator, however, does not rule against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these companies bring them non-negligible benefits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, in the manner of the ordinary customers of mobile operators."
That is precisely what should seem strange to the ČTÚ.
In addition, there is another question to the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to disclose such an activity, and if it does not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions forbid it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned on several occasions, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable drop in the price of services.
However, in virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, traditional operators tried, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were virtually the same - a market that was too small, if not too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that regulatory bodies in developed countries have intervened, not defending the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both formal measures and informal pressure resulted in the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulatory agencies are treating this issue like a hot potato that is being disposed of by passing it on to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than beneficial to them in these cases.
But let's not throw the sleeve after the punch.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear in our home, the Czech mobile market may get back on the move.
If one of the operators has accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will hardly be able to remain impassible in the face of the rejection (of discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling it more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Czech Citizenship Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was recorded again by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Ji+ Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo song, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The singing is performed by Kateřina Kn+nková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the server iHned.cz.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national singing one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose for the performance solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to take care that the two singers, as well as the choir, had a good diction, so that the words could be understood correctly, that they could sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj first sounded in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetteiers), an original Czech play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škrup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse naturally became part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
