Pragois public transport (MHD) will introduce the chip into their ticketing system on Wednesday
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be recorded in the history of the Pražský Dopravní podnik (the Prague Transport Agency) as the date on which the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, which, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, it is accessible for about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day or 90-day coupon (this coupon will be valid from 1 January 2009) and both have it registered on their smart card in the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (Transport Agency), located in the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádra+ Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Let+any, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
From yesterday, there is also the possibility to buy coupons by internet on the web pages of the Dopravní podnik: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people took advantage of the service during the morning.
Those who start using the online store can finally forget the ticket counters in the metro stations, where they had to trample impatiently in long queues so far in order to get paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their coupon by internet and will be recorded on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"In these contact points, passengers are provided with a counter with trained staff, who will help them with the purchase via the internet and, in addition, will record the coupon they bought on their card," says the spokesperson for the Martin Optrný project.
Besides libraries, it will also be possible to record electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, remind the machines to compost the tickets and the passengers have perhaps already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today the city has five, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," added Optrný.
An automaton will control the coupon instead of the driver
The automatons that will work from tomorrow are easy to use.
Simply introduce the Opencard smart card and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
The electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the vicinity of the city.
