The Sudetes called for a referendum in the USA
The Germans of the Sudetes demanded in 1945 that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This follows from a letter filed in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of the Southern Bohemian).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, certain groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly addressed the president of the United States with such a desire.
This stems, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov ask in the letter the American President not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and want to be truly sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, signed "People, to whom the fate of the Šumava is close to heart".
Since the rallying of Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, disrespectful attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take in his hands the protectorate of Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state that oppresses and destroys minorities and that has in no way contributed to the victory of the Allies without taking into consideration the opinion of the quarter of a million inhabitants," is written in the letter.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the president of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans in Šumava, he would simply have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the United States, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, in view of current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the then Sudeten Germans.
While the Czech Germans had at least to see that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some were waiting for the United States and Great Britain to gain some kind of autonomy for the Sudetes.
Others believed that they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them," said Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, according to him, felt that, following Beneš decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
You're not thinking - you're paying!
An emotional campaign will attack drivers
The most expensive road safety action in Czech history.
A way of characterising the emotional media campaign that the Ministry of Transport intends to launch on Wednesday.
The Office of Minister Aleš Öebüek believes that it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving behaviour.
This campaign costing 150 million will appear on television, radio, cinema, the internet, but also on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from driving quickly and driving alcohol.
But also remind them to take the belt before starting.
Above all, it wants to touch the consciousness of young drivers, bikers, pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the spots?
Especially personal stories that will attack emotions.
This is also reflected in the "bloody" slogan of the whole campaign:
You're not thinking - you're paying!
The phrase "You don't think" is capitalized on the license plate.
Then, in a puddle of blood, there's the phrase "You'll pay."
Which must symbolize that one can pay for life for a moment of inattention.
The spots will "hanter" the spectators until 2010.
The ministry has been inspired by similar campaigns in Anglo-Saxon countries, where one can see commonly images with drastic images of the victims of accidents.
He believes that this will lead to a decrease in the rate of accidents and the number of deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the Euro RSCG agency.
The strategy of sugar and whip against drivers
"What works with drivers is the system of sugar and whip.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by saving time when they burn a red light.
The whip is the threat of a fine or an accident.
The risks must be reminded to the drivers," says Martin Ko+n, the transport psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
This is how we need information campaigns in the press and, above all, negative advertisements, according to the psychologist.
According to him, signs that signal danger to drivers are already less effective.
"When a static panel that warns against a danger is installed, it will probably soon merge with the environment and the drivers won't notice it again," Ko+n said.
