Nights of insomnia for Hypo Real Estate shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted only a few weeks ago.
What a chance that the politician used the word 'relatively' and slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared by the crisis movements.
This one happened this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), on the side of the DAX, obtains a credit of one billion from a consortium of German banks to protect itself from market turbulence.
One person in the confidence of the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are granted up to EUR 35 billion.
The Hypo Real Estate should now pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
In the background, the company-daughter Depfa bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible since the mistrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve had been reduced from 95 per cent to EUR 2.37 million, and the own capital rate had also decreased slightly from 1.6 per cent to 1.45 per cent.
Current and net profits from financial transactions had fallen to zero from the same period in the previous year, profits from the allocation of specified receivables and securities and the termination of provisions in credit transactions had fallen from more than 70 per cent to EUR 5 million.
And it was only because of the large profits from the repayment of the downstream accounting costs resulting from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as from the repayment of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for the Konzern companies that the earnings deficit of about 16 percent proved to be moderate.
After its privatisation in 1990, the former state financier had initially miscured on industrial loans for real estate, which had subsequently been filialized at Aareaal Bank.
Because conventional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa had subsequently become more involved in infrastructure projects and in joint financing between private investors and the state (Privat-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the company-daughter, the Hypo Real Estate must carry out depreciations which should have on the calculation of the gains and losses of the group an essential material effect which remains nevertheless rather vague.
The fact is that the dividends have been cut.
Already for 2007, they had been truncated by two thirds.
Since the acquisition of Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other institutions dependent on refinancing in the interbank market since it has no customer deposits.
With the bankruptcy of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of credit between banks again fell considerably, the banks having accumulated their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs an annual part - about 50 billion euros - of all Depfa's loans for a short-term refinancing average.
According to a statement from Hypo Real Estate, the group's financing requirement is covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of international financial markets which are currently largely out of working order.
Other sources say that refinancing would be ensured through the funds until the end of 2009.
