"I photograph the master out of the scene to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no clothes of bow.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these unknown moments of the general public, where we discover with intimate gestures and stolen eyes artists who do not care to go on stage.
German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of a few stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer takes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programme of the Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists able to transmit on stage passion, sadness, joy ... by captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists it is not necessary to make photos on stage.
They have their own personality and character.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera moments of personality of flamenco stars ".
With the festival "Chant populaire des Mines", Bauer began a long journey in 1997 to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, remakes classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises each day".
It is not about dancing or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the public with his art.
The search for essentials and magic has been the constant of this work that is presented these days at the gallery El Fotómata.
Flamenco stars like Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project has turned into a flamenco anthology, which will soon be published in a book collecting portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits de vieux sportifs" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a more or less long time.
I think that in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you don't know or that just give you a few minutes to get a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the Galerie El Fotómata, located at number 20 of the rue de la Mata (rue parallel to the Peupleraie d'Hercule) which will be open until October 16.
