Recidivists of alcohol driving will have to install the 'alcolock' system
The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative penalties for alcoholism to have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the vehicle from starting in a state of intoxication, or if it does not blow.
The initiative was already announced last June and it now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project that will last one year.
Its aim is to reintegrate the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State responsible for road safety but also the Directorate-General for Road Safety and the Technological Institute for Motor Vehicle Safety will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists arrested for driving more than once in a state of drunkenness, take over the car.
The alcolock would avoid this since it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the breath alcohol level and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not blow forward; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than that allowed.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is at the driver's expense.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced offences by up to 65% in the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save the lives of 115 people each year.
This is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: dealing with these behaviours before they turn into criminal offences.
And to facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done by ordinary means but, however, reform by criminal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote an initiative of the Spanish Socialist Party which proposes to install this system in school buses as it was done in France.
