Sarkozy meets angry fishermen
Before flying to the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will make a detour by Brittany.
Faced with the demonstration of strength of the fishermen who strongly disrupted the access of several Breton and Norman ports on Monday, the President of the Republic decided to go Tuesday morning to the port of Guilvinec, in the Finistère, to meet their representatives.
They promised to welcome it "in a constructive spirit" and hope that it "will come with concrete proposals".
A presidential visit which falls at the same time as a general assembly of the "crisis committee" set up by Breton fishermen to obtain measures in the face of the soaring prices of diesel fuel, which reached a record level of more than 1.14 euro per litre on average.
According to the spokesperson for lElysée David Martinon, the president "will discuss with them solutions that can be imagined to help their companies regain competitiveness and to secure the conditions of employment and remuneration of sailors".
Nicolas Sarkozy is expected to stand firm by the fishermen.
Tuesday morning, they conducted snail operations in Morbihan and Calvados, causing traffic jams of almost 10 km.
The marina of Quiberon was also blocked, but the connections to Belle-Île were not stopped.
A filtering dam has been set up on the Quiberon Peninsula.
The sailors have already shown their determination on Monday by burning tires and pallets in front of the fuel depots of the ports of Brest, and Lorient, as early as dawn, while demonstrations were taking place in Concarneau or Saint-Brieuc.
The movement has spread to other ports on the Atlantic facade and the Channel, such as Les Sables d'Olonne, in Vendée, where trawlers have remained docked, or Le Havre, where some 20 boats have blocked the movements of commercial vessels.
The fishermen of La Turballe and the Croisic, in the Loire-Atlantique, stopped the blockade of the important Total Donges refinery in the evening.
Those in Boulogne-sur-Mer decided to wait until Wednesday's meeting at the ministry to decide on possible actions.
In Guilvinec, the "crisis committee" must decide Tuesday on the follow-up to be given to the movement and its participation in the interview scheduled at the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by officials of the National Fisheries Committee, who did not support their movement.
"The strike will continue" because "the fishermen will not let go" and "don't want to travel to Paris," said Liliane Cariou, president of the Lorient Fisheries Committee.
Professional fishermen, who do not pay taxes on diesel, currently pay about 50 cents per litre but they estimate that the profitability threshold of a boat is only reached with a diesel less than 0.30 euro per litre.
