In Minsk, "Did you notice there was an election?"
Young people and opponents were protesting on Sunday evening in the main square of the Belarusian capital to reject in advance the results of the legislative elections.
A few hundred Belarusians met on Sunday evening as soon as the polling stations closed in central Minsk to protest against the fraudulent nature of the legislative elections.
While no results had yet been announced, many young people had come to protest against the power of President Alexander Lukashenko: "the dictator, resignation".
Some admit that they did not even vote: "What good is it, since they will do what they want with my voice," says a young man.
They do not believe that the regime that has been good for foreign observers in order to resume language with the European Union is ready to make a democratic turning point.
Sanctions, including the ban on visas for 40 Belarusian leaders and the freezing of certain assets, could be lifted if these elections were considered by observers to be clean.
They were not, according to the opposition.
"We were kept away from the electoral commissions and our observers were not able to participate in the counting," lamented Yuuri Potemkin, spokesman for the Union of Democratic Forces, a heterogeneous grouping of twelve parties.
"This is a cosmetic change," said Alexandre Milinkievitch, former opposition candidate for the 2006 presidential election and leader of the pro-European movement, "because the important thing is who counts the votes, and in our country, it is the executive power.
If opposition deputies enter parliament, they will have been appointed, not elected.
But their entry into parliament can mean space on television, meetings in the regions and proposals for legislation."
The opposition must therefore enter into the political game because "the dialogue with the European Union must begin.
For if our economy, which is heavily indebted to Russia, goes into crisis, and we do not reform, we risk becoming a protectorate of Russia.
But we want to be independent."
The opposition is concerned that the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe that followed the electoral process may recognize the validity of the election.
She pointed out that participation figures seemed too high, and that the generalisation of advance voting (26% of the voters in Minsk) had opened the vote to all manipulations.
"You noticed that there was an election, you?" asked Social Democratic leader Alexandre Kozoulin, one of the last two political prisoners released in August of this year.
There was no one in the polling stations.
And there will be no more than five opposition MPs in parliament, those who are best suited to power."
The silence of the night falls back on the square of October.
On television, President Lukashenko and the members of the Central Electoral Commission welcome their success.
The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec was celebrating yesterday the 10th anniversary of its founding, and its president, Dr.Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, as Héma-Québec became one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
Most importantly, he regained the public confidence that had been seriously shaken by the blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and the grunt of the public, the Government of Canada initiated in February 1994 a public inquiry, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations that such a disaster should not happen again.
While Justice Krever was late in tabling his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Services to supply all other provinces and territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began operations, only 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was disheartening.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground in the years that followed, we regained public confidence," she said before proudly asserting that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile."
From its inception on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of mad cow disease were emerging in Europe, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, recounts the one that has held the fort since its founding in 1998.
"And we did not know at all whether this disease could be transmitted through blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when this is not known and a serious disease can result, Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain leading inevitably to death, measures of exclusion are introduced.
As a result, in April 1999, blood was refused for those who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, however, it was shown beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted through blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV testing technique emerged on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which directly detect the presence of the virus itself in the blood of donors and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, upon which the tests used so far were based.
The NATs made it possible to shorten the silent period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period could be reduced to less than one week.
This substantially reduced the risk that some donors would be infected without knowing it and could not be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission from a blood product occurs.
I believe that today we can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover our health," says the Chief Executive Officer of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than last year on Reunion Island the Chikungunya virus, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," says Dr. Décary before pointing out that in addition to a secure supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supplies.
"Needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
Because anticancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cells or platelets to recharge.
The aging population also affects the blood donor network, which accounts for an average of only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation."
A healthy person, 18 years of age or older who meets the eligibility criteria, can still give blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of those who offer their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a malaria-affected country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer give blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to give blood, but especially to hold them back and encourage them to become regular donors.
Since today's life is so unbridled, we rarely find time to spend an hour giving blood," desolates Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukaemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth sample of cord blood and we plan to collect more than one thousand a year.
We should start proposing them for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood program as very popular.
"Several mothers are disappointed to be unable to access it", because Héma-Québec cannot afford to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
