Charest bet on the North
The Prime Minister does not rule out calling elections before the end of the year
As soon as the general council of the Liberal Party was finished, Jean Charest visited Jean-Talon in Quebec City yesterday, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (left), is trying to get elected in today's by-election.
"Removing the boundaries of our last great frontier in the north": this is the long-term ambition that Jean Charest presented with visual force while remaining in broad outline, at the end of the general council of the Liberal Party of Quebec, in Lévis yesterday.
Behind him, during his speech, was projected a sort of picture mill.
In a loop, on three huge screens, spectacular shots of hydroelectric dams, mining, Quebec seen by "Google Maps", maps, etc.
Great means as in election times.
In the press, moreover, the Prime Minister refused to exclude that he would call the elections this fall, even though he pointed out that his schedule was very busy.
The "Plan Nord" is the fourth part of a "vision" that the Prime Minister claims to have for Quebec, that of a "new economic space", which includes a labour agreement with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe and agreements with Ontario.
Often mentioned in the Prime Minister's speeches recently, the opening of the North - the northern territory in the 49th parallel - had never been the subject of a presentation.
The Prime Minister, however, simply explained why the North was "a jewel with immense potential", but did not set a deadline, investment amounts, or specific priority in future projects.
At most a few avenues of what could be further developed: notably hydroelectricity, forest, but especially the mining sector, boosted by the growth of emerging countries and the reconstruction of public infrastructure.
The North contains "nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium, and even diamond", according to Mr. Charest's enumeration.
This "territory twice as big as France", "it's our home, it's in Quebec.
Not only is it home, but it's in us," he insisted, as if to show that he was asking for a national founding myth.
Quebec has built up a lot in its relationship with the North, he pointed out: the gold rush in Abitibi, Quebec engineering, James Bay.
"It's ours, it's our future," he added, after taking a theatrical break to contemplate the immense map behind him.
The North, 70% of Quebec's territory, includes a portion of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, said the Prime Minister at the press briefing.
"This is a traditional position that all governments have reiterated.
There is a border line on which there has been no agreement for a very long time and, when the opportunity arises, I reiterate that position on behalf of the government," he said.
Moreover, "with climate change, we need to rethink our vision of the North," he said, referring to the Northwest Passage, which will open all year round due to the melting of the ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister believes that occupying the territory is a duty.
What about the people of the Territory, First Nations and Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Government of Quebec would be very attentive to them and that the project would benefit them, especially young people.
Two former ministers from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former Pequist MP for Ungava), have already begun consultations with some thirty communities.
An interdepartmental committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier and in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) has an important place has begun work.
The Prime Minister does not exclude a great meeting, "not necessarily a summit", but a moment when "a common vision will be given".
The development of the North would be in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
The Plan Nord will be "concerted, orderly and environmentally friendly", he promised.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as being in continuity with that of the Liberal prime minister who preceded it.
"Like the Liberals who preceded us, we thought differently to turn challenges into new opportunities for growth and development."
This was one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which began Friday with a big cocktail to mark the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage's arrival at the head of the party.
One of the resolutions adopted proposes to rename the Beauharnois Centrale in Adélard-Godbout Dam.
"From Godbout, who created Hydro-Québec, to Lesage who made the Quiet Revolution and the Nationalization of Hydroelectricity, to Bourassa who made James Bay, our party was able to forge the future," said Jean Charest.
In the press, he cited another reference, conservative this one, the "Roads to the North" program of John Diefenbaker, Prime Minister from 1957 to 1963.
In approaching the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam project, Mr.Charest noted that its commissioning was scheduled for 2012.
"It stays between us, but I plan to be there," he told his activists, causing them to be applauded.
Indeed, the Prime Minister, who said in April that there would be no election in 2008 and probably not in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of calling an election this fall, which the law allows.
He pointed out, however, that his schedule was fulfilled, notably by a mission of the federation council to China and a Québec-New York summit.
The General Council of the weekend provided the Liberal leader with a platform containing nationalist resolutions, including "constitutional aspirations" that passed as a letter to the post office: the PLQ in particular calls for recognition of the "specificity of Quebec" in the Constitution.
He also hoped that Quebec would appoint members of the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission and that they would have the right to veto decisions made in Quebec.
On the opposition side, the main lines of the Plan Nord were greeted with scepticism.
The Pequist leader, Pauline Marois, emerged from the Northern Quebec Development Policy launched by the Landry government in 2001.
According to her, the Liberal government, when it came to power in 2003, gave up its application.
If he had done so, "we would be more advanced today" commented Mrs. Marois alongside her candidate in Jean-Talon (scrutin that is taking place today), Françoise Mercure.
The ADQ expressed support for the government's adoption of a North Plan.
"But what we want is that it isn't just a show," commented leader Sébastien Proulx, replacing Mario Dumont, who is coming back from vacation today.
