Free opinion - The Orwellian speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice President of Canadian Mining Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has brought a defamation suit of six million against three authors and a small publishing house without a penny in order to launch a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation prosecutions, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr Garver.
For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to lead to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and the publisher of Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defence and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of mining.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an amicable settlement that will gag the opposition in addition to frightening anyone who dares to look again at the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada normally take place through the exchange of ideas and not through batons.
It was therefore enough for mining to open its books, its files and to establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support to Black Canada authors.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he could both ask for a "public" debate while ignoring the views of the same public?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to lawyers who are highly paid and not to all Canadians; this is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In democracy, even critics have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports Black Canada's authors and publishers does so primarily because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a gag chase (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has also just put out a warning against Black Canada writers intimidating them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Garver's surreal discourse, the pursuit of Barrick Gold is a direct attack on academic research freedom and the quest for truth, which are essential to any democratic society.
It denies, as a whole, the right to quote credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss issues that displease the rich companies of this world in a country like Canada, under pain of repeated prosecution, who will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could do so by following the scientific standards used by Black Canada authors.
She has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has a long history of managing debates and disagreements and resolving conflicts.
The disproportionate pursuit of Barrick Gold clearly shows that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss to the academic world, as well as to public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and Congress leaders, both Republican and Democratic, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new US$700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been rocking Wall Street for months still needs to be endorsed by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it provides for better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of the public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for failure to pay, and a right of scrutiny of the salaries paid to the managers of the companies rescued.
The U.S. Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to protect the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is the fundamental point: if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and disruptions on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had turned into a sprint in the last few hours for fear of the effect that a new failure would have on the mood of investors.
The deadline was for the opening of the markets this morning.
Lately associated with the negotiations, the two candidates in the US presidential election were rather in favour of the agreement, but they did not fail to express their dissatisfaction that they were forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama agreed to add some provisions to the agreement, including the agreement to allow homeowners to keep their homes and the agreement on the salaries of government-backed business leaders.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be welcomed.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on American television.
Asked on another channel to find out if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The outlines I have read [show] that this is something that we will all have to digest and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable," he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to redeem with taxpayers' money the doubtful, risky and unsold debts of U.S. financial institutions.
After 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble which first led to the collapse of risk mortgages (subprimes) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAA) and resulting in a liquidity freeze and the debanda of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of elected Republicans who had wrecked the first draft agreement last week.
It is believed that this impasse has been overcome since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round off the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added stating that if the government were to bear losses for five years with this program, it could introduce new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion to which may be added another 100 billion if the President deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion should be approved by another Congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will obtain shares in the rescued companies that will earn him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to resell when the turmoil passes.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay the seizure procedures for housing related to the real estate loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on the remuneration and severance benefits paid to the managers of the affected businesses.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the vote of the House of Representatives today, and to that of the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Votes continued yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camp.
"Obviously Washington can't hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, to his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that is to benefit the taxpayers."
Moderator of a small group in Congress dubbed "the caucus of skeptics", Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent economics professors, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to tell us: we are asking Congress not to rush and to examine carefully the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again proof of the global nature of the crisis.
After an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the banking group Fortis for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg had been made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas had indicated that it was refusing to acquire its competitor in the midst of a shipwreck since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the crisis of mortgages at risk in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the 20 largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"This is not money lost," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
In exchange, we get back a right to vote in the bank and influence.
It is precisely something that savers and households now appreciate that the times are uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be nationalizing another bank misled by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all outstanding loans from Bradford and Bringley Bank, including more than 41 billion (75.5 billion US) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would purchase the branches and accounts receivable of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
His beauty in the eyes of azure was for a long time his asset card, some will say his weakness.
Had he freed himself from the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with a charming smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, his sensitivity and a talent that flowed from the source will also have distanced him from the power register that gives birth to true sacred monsters.
But what a great runner!
Paul Newman, who disappeared on Friday, at the age of 83, from lung cancer in his Connecticut ranch, remains one of the last icons of American cinema of the fascination years.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of which he was for a long time a kind of rival on the screen, more careful in his game, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the break-up of dramatic conventions.
The mixed bloods often make beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925, to a German Jewish father and a Hungarian mother of origin.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, ultimate quality brand.
For in him a whole country of self-made man, of the combatant of the Pacific War, wounded in combat, who in the early 1950s studied dramatic art at Yale and then attended the Actor's Studio in New York, before triumphing at the theatre, on television, soon at the cinema.
The same man who militated for civil rights was also the motor driver who finished second in the 24 hours of Le Mans in 1979, coupled with a sex symbol, although a member of a model couple formed since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
Also disappear with him the shadows of this secret star, discreet, committed, allergic to the flashes of the show-business, of which we will not have completely pierced the enigma.
An honest man, in the most noble sense of the word.
The disappearance of Paul Newman gave the cinemaphiles vertigo this weekend, as his great roles clashed on the black screen of memories.
More than half a century of a seventh American art in perpetual mutation unfolds through it.
Return to remember the charming cowboy of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in La Chatte on a burning roof adapted from Tennessee Williams in 1958.
Closer to us (1990), we evoke his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in his old age by a marriage that did not fulfill all his promises.
