This boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Somebody Up There Likes Me, by Robert Wise, a role for James Dean, taken over after his death, who really launched Newman in 1956.
This friendly villain in the brilliant The Sting (L'Arnaque), Oscar of the best film in 1973.
A bitter billiard player and vengeful in Robert Rossen's The Hustler (1961), he took over the character on his return to Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which won him his only Oscar on nine nominations in 1987.
That face through the ages, it was him.
He's still here.
The eras rushed through his path.
Young people know him mostly through George Roy Hill's Slap Shot (1977), in Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers.
With a final role as sponsor of the Irish mafia in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003, the loop was closed.
In contrast to several cinema legends who soon let go of the trade, Newman remained in the saddle for a long time, while denouncing Hollywood, its golds, its fastes and its concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered him, not without humor, "as a living challenge to "underplaying" considering his performances too supported.
The profession was not always tender for the handsome Paul Newman to whom the roles long fell all cooked in the beak.
However, he played less often the early young than the marginal ones: neurotic, alcoholic, bastard or desperate, whose perfect traits reflected drifts and revolts.
As a director, Newman revealed poorly known facets of his true modest sensitivity.
His Rachel, Rachel, in 1968 (according to the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the lead, drew a fine female portrait of melancholy.
He who lost his son Scott by overdose dedicated his film Harry and Son to him in 1984, a work of modesty and sadness.
Among the rain of tributes yesterday on Newman, his great friend and former arms companion Robert Redford (they had played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said, very saddened: "His presence made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of existence are vibrant traits of the disappeared actor.
Beyond his career as a legend, he also erases a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester of Hollywood drifts.
We'll have seen a lot of her booze on dressing pots, sauces, biscuits and other foods, judging the process to be quite tasteless, though gag at first.
The profits from these sales were nevertheless paid to his Foundation for Children in Difficulty.
Newman, rather than sit on his myth, will have committed himself to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter containing these sentences: "Always and until the end, your father was incredibly grateful for his good star.
It was a privilege to be here."
