What could Zuschlag &amp; Company make in their invoice factory?
Soon, on 8 October, the hearings relating to the ongoing criminal proceedings will begin against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, resulting in particularly serious damage. Other charges have been brought against them, such as forgery and the use of forgery.
According to the Public Prosecutor's Office, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The state and municipal money, about HUF 65 million in total, went on the one hand in the funds of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other, in the pocket of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to collect the money from the subsidies obtained by issuing cost invoices, behind which no actual services were provided and thus the associations never complied with their commitments.
According to the indictment, a large part of the invoices were false.
For the latter, they obtained invoice books from the Józsefváros market, while they made the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that would appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the tours in the northern province of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's testimony, he had to locate pensions and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they made the other invoices that they would introduce, among other things, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, and the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András
During a "tracking circuit", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlags in 2003, this place restored a group of 90 people, members of the Biztos Pont Egyesület association.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which later became known as Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért, was full of errors of form and substance.
A board, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and up to ten people could spend the night there. However, the bill mentioned one hundred and thirty guests.
The over-imagining bill issuers also fell into excess when they mentioned Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. Neither the name of Jobb Jövőért nor the name of Hoppá appeared in their accounts, according to the information given to the prosecution.
Győző Farkas, the manager of the company, told the website hvg.hu that when the prosecutor summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew immediately that they were false documents.
"The name of our company and our tax number were placed in a wrong place on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that according to the bill, a hundred people had lodged there, also did not stick, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much room.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
The senders of zealous invoices also did not find out about the Budapest travel agencies, being part of their choice, but only organizing trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also goes against the accounting practices of the agency.
From a surprise, as it appeared during the survey, they also added VAT on these documents, while services relating to travel activities, whose destination is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices drawn up in the name of the Hotel Revfülöp to the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's services do not bear a 25% VAT, but a 15% VAT. Moreover, the employees of the hotel issue only printed invoices, while the fakes were written by hand.
The public prosecutor's inquiry reveals that the "issuers" also made mistakes by mentioning as delivery the transport of goods by road, which the company issuing the invoices could not exercise, since its profile was the investment consultancy.
Moreover, it is also for defects of form, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that the invoices issued to the order of Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont have proved to be false.
Just as in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó's sports course, which both deny being the authors of the invoices issued on their behalf.
The forgers also did not pay attention to the fact that the company HIB Kft., based in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time (in 2001) the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have a meal at home. According to our information, it is for this reason that the liquidator of the company denies having issued this invoice.
Deliberately established invoices
Another category of invoice issuers is that composed of those who were fully aware that they were asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esely Budapestert Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták group, has issued an invoice to the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért for a sum of HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the manager of Collab Kft. was forced to issue false invoices by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, it cooperated with the Zuschlags, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently being wound up and which in 2003 issued invoices to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, Atlasz Egyesület Association and Vörösfenyő Egyesület Association, for an amount of approximately HUF 5 million, but behind which no services were actually provided.
No financial movement took place, either, as the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but this was avoided by the organizations in their accounts.
The next category of invoice companies is that of companies directly related to the accused.
Thus, the administrative representative of the general manager of Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the trade in fuel and motor vehicles, whose head office was in Budapest, but where he could not be found, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, the equipment was purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of the company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Iván Kubatov also allegedly sent documents relating to the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov acknowledged during the investigation that he issued invoices to Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he took their value.
It was precisely at the request of Iván Kubatov that Romanian masons created Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In fact, none of these companies were functioning, as the accused explains by the fact that they did not receive work.
He still used these companies, since at the request of Master Zsolt Szente, co-defendant as well as editor of the founding documents of the companies, he drew up invoices in their names, to the order of associations relating to Zuschlag, such as the Atlasz and Y-Generáció associations.
Kubatov gave a total of 15 invoices to organizations issued by Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, worth HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecution believed that 10% of the sums shown on the invoices as well as VAT went in Kubatov's pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to draw up fictitious invoices which were used in the context of the grant application of Biztos Pont.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért Association applied to Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA) of the Socialist Party for a grant.
They obtained this grant for twice HUF 500,000, but these amounts were not used for the purposes indicated in the application.
To avoid this, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
Moreover, these invoices were found during the search carried out in the office of Árpád Kemecsei, Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the accused will relate the method of making the invoices, as they had already done before the prosecution.
What might be really interesting would be that the main defendant, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil on the whole story.
So far, his confessions are not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to tell the smallest details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or, possibly, the Socialists would have reached an agreement that in exchange for the reimbursement of a large part of the HUF 50 million, Zusi would carry the hat alone.
Today, he is probably offended, since requests for house arrest, based on a reduction in his conditions of detention, are continually falling into the ear of a deaf person.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and those who commit economic crimes that are not repairable, walk freely or at least, wait in their own homes for the end of the proceedings. He does not have that possibility.
The psychology of bidding: why is more money spent?
During auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Neurology and economics researchers at the University of New York have been able to update the neurological and economic foundations of this known and apparently irrational behaviour.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be distanced during this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research has attempted to draw up a neurological scheme of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, while the other group took part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, one essential element of which is the over-auction of a third party, the whole under the brainstem, called striatum, moved intensively when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the mechanism of "self-stimulation" of the nervous system.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers continued financial surveillance analyses.
During these events, three groups overpriced against a partner, under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they thus carried out their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they would win the game, then they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
While the third group received this $15 before the auction, the group members also lost this money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is that the emphasis was in one group on victory, while in the other, on failure.
By thus proving the hypothesis of neurologists, the members of the team of players "against failure" were prepared to bet higher than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade before the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation." - Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at New York University, noted.
Hepatitis: When should we consult a doctor?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary chronic liver disease is mentioned as one of the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that hundreds of thousands of people are infected with the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven thousand are receiving treatment. This is due to the fact that often the patients do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases produced differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to pathogenic genes, are mainly spread in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended that they be vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no C vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated foods, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, stools become lighter and urine becomes darker. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Every year around the world, one million people die of the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that according to estimates, only one in ten patients is receiving medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know about the virus, because the pathogen destroys the liver cells in a sneaky way. In many cases, the first symptoms do not appear until after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion prior to 1991, drug users and tattooed people.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic type C hepatitis worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult with your treating physician as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if it is detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its objective is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does anyone who grows in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would function as a sort of analgesic, which had already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British daily Telegraph published an article according to which researchers at Oxford University made an interesting experiment by analyzing at what level belief in God could influence tolerance to human pain.
As part of this bizarre experiment, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also possible to discover that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More specifically, the experiment takes place in the following way: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing the electroshocks is attached to the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to watch two paintings in a sustained way, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with ermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers at the origin of this experiment hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary evoked a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, concerned its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time received 20 electroshocks in four successive parts, while watching either the religious theme painting or the more general theme painting.
The Catholics said that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt as "in safety", as someone of whom we "take care of" and they "quieted, and peace invaded them".
In view of the painting of religious themes, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonard's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, thinks that one can achieve the same effects with any other strong image, in atheists, provided that one finds the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image against which they react very positively, such as a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, praised the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases actually changes our personality," added Wright.
After these excellent results, there is only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of subjects if one shows believers a Madonna painted by Leonard or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would seeing a better Virgin Mary result in better results?
You're what you disclose about yourself.
On the occasion of its tenth anniversary, Google says that it can be found in the bottom of people's pockets in the same way as the sky above their heads. It knows where they spent their holidays, which specialists they consult and what are their interests.
It is not yet enough, according to Eric Schmidt, who is one of the influential people of society.
While as far as skeptics are concerned, establishing a parallel with Orwell's horror vision, they do not see the essence of web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main ambition is to gather even more information about its users. This is necessary for Google founders to meet their original goal, which sounded like "Let's get all the world's information back into a system!".
According to the Google leader interviewed, after ten years of global upheaval work, they are still only at the beginning of their goals of being able to process all the information.
To the question: what will be there in five years? Schmidt replied that he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "What could I do tomorrow?" or "What is the job that would be best for me?" However, the software will only be able to answer this kind of question, simple at first glance, when they know enough about the users.
It is not perfectly clear to all Internet users that the words used during Internet searches, the IP address of the computer that initiates the search and the pages consulted by the interested persons are precisely listed.
Through the Personalized Search program launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can view what they have been looking for, what they have clicked on. Thanks to this, in the long term, Recommendations, a program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized answers, and will submit products and services to us based on our previous statements and our registered preferences.
What happens if someone uses my data against me, if he looks at what my job is? Ask users, who are worried about Google's monopoly of information.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can cause fear, and it is not remorse, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or possibly revolt against power that can cause Internet users to counter-reaction.
However, it is a confirmed fact that the terms sought are not only registered, but in justified cases, they are transmitted to a third party, and in such legal cases, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most striking example of recent times is probably the coordinated action against Brazilian paedophiles, during which Google transmitted to the Brazilian government the information it had collected on the public page called Orkut, thus allowing identification.
Human rights-conscious Internet users were able to sigh a sigh of relief last May, when Google, with the electronic legal protection agency EFF, proved its right in court against the FBI. According to the judgment rendered, in the future, Google will still not be forced by any of the points of the constitution to disclose information about the FBI's secret request of any kind.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms it had won in relation to the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier. But in the end, it fails to obtain lists of searches of private users, nor the entire list of websites and keywords of the past two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is castigated by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their intimate sphere and private domain suffer from it when they start using Google services. Therefore, they attack them in the spirit of revolt that is manifested against multinational companies proud of their conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its "savageons" bringing together passionate, activists and enthusiastic computer users who appear in many countries see Google as the next generation of big companies, the "connected body", as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, catalogued as an invader of the world because of Windows, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
This can be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for identification code, does not ask for money for its applications. The document code and package of programs, continually refreshed, has a much more accessible, younger and cooler effect, compared to the practice of the official software giant.
The reason may also be that geeks see very exactly the problematic relationship between human rights and the Internet, and what web 2.0, the most proclaimed keyword of recent years, is just behind it.
Indeed, web 2.0 does not concern anything other than collaboration, that the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind us, and that we use the channels of communication made available to us, and while the dimension of these changes one by one, the essential remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person, in general, can hold a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link them to other services, such as Twinter, or to last.fm, listing his musical habits. Then, he can link them to a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also hold blogs, in which appear automatically their newest photo galleries that they store on Flickr or Picasa.
While we can see many examples, such as that of the girlfriend who easily understands the pictures of the morning, taken by the circle of common friends, with whom her unfaithful friend spent the evening, or that of the company that dismissed one of his employees, just for the sincere opinions that he wrote on his blog about top management, we can be sure of one thing: the term privacy is totally to be reconsidered nowadays.
He who lives an online life is made up of what he shows by himself, and this is how one can define the principle hiding behind the behaviour of today's young people.
One wants to hide something, or at least, wants to try to bypass Google's monopoly, can do so (starting, for example, with Scroogle, using Google's search system, but at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who deliberately do not register on public pages so that it is not possible to find them is not the least. Google’s online services, including text processing, image processing and reading of information, can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not linked to huge server parks and which do not assemble our best profile, which have existed to date.
Public opinion is waiting, without really hiding, for the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
The company, with its current value of $156 billion, is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion). AdWords/AdSense advertising fields threaten the turnover of advertising agencies, while the services introduced at an increasing speed cause serious migraines not only to Microsoft, but to many other creators of computer programs.
In addition to all this, however, critical observers find contradictions with worrying effects: for example, the company's top management refused, in its entirety, the protests of the employees, after it doubled the price of the kindergarten and after the company considered the daily multiple restoration, taken at any time, to be too expensive. All this seems ridiculous in addition to the fact that already in 2006, Google acquiesced before the Chinese government and according to the terms of their agreement, the company detects all the results that hurt the good taste, as well as the interests of the Chinese regime.
According to one of the company's internal rules, the new services are not announced only when they can be used. What is sure is that in the coming months and years, they will move the world on new points. While some think that Google's scanning and archiving project of books and magazines is taking on such important dimensions that the company will soon find itself facing the Supreme Court of the United States, others tremble at its Health system, because in it, we can build a complete medical profit from our previous analysis results, our doctors and our problems.
The fact that Google is setting up a genetic database can give a good raw material to the next generation of science fiction authors. The novel of the famous Cory Doctorow, written with Orwellian half-tones, describes the future in which a man could be approached in a frightening way just through Google data.
