The intelligent automobile mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What method would be better to develop technologies that are able to avoid an obstacle, other than the imitation of an existing obstacle detector in nature?
Like, for example, the bees'.
In the amazing project presented at the CATEC, held in Japan, the buzzing bees gave the start strategic idea to Nissan engineers, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle sensors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-roboted system, of type BR23C, which it has equipped with qualities of bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee constitutes its own space, oval-shaped, which in reality, looks much like our secure protection shell - explained, during the exhibition, Kazuhhiro Doi, the director of the department of technological research and development and public relations of the brand.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a crucial role, since it is able to see in all directions, in an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the faceted eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser telemeter.
It identifies obstacles in an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, it evaluates the distances and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor, which turns it into an avoidance manoeuvre immediately.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it with a sufficient angle to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance manoeuvre is entirely instinctive.
"If it wasn't for that, the mini auto robot wouldn't be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and internal layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment the collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go up, down or diagonally, it can only be of two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees possess to avoid other bees, in our case, we were only able to use the rotary motion, acceleration and slow down as manoeuvres at the disposal of the mini auto robot
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a greater concentration of energy, making their lifetime longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not data processing, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should deal with only a few incoming signals per second, and react to them.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on the data of previous manoeuvres. In this way, it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We don't need memory of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of an instant avoidance technology. Nissan estimates that this system will enter mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
