"An overwhelming majority of young Roma do not have secondary school diplomas, and as a result of poor quality elementary education, only a tiny part of them have the possibility of obtaining a higher education diploma."
In addition, Járóka stressed that education as a basic human right plays a key role in the exercise of other fundamental rights.
Investment in the early education of Roma children means strengthening the economies of the member countries of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise awareness of these relationships in as wide a circle as possible, also between Roma and non-Roma.
The earlier a Roma child starts school, the more likely he or she is to become a productive member of the labour market; by taxes paid from income and consumption, he or she participates in the State budget.
"By virtue of their citizenship of the European Union, Roma must be guaranteed their right to quality education, and be protected from low quality and sectarian education." - Lívia Járóka stressed.
According to the MEP, the European Union's cooperation towards an objective and action is necessary for an immediate acceleration of the process of desegregation of schools. To this end, compliance with the existing anti-discrimination directives and in preparation is of paramount importance.
"The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and the unemployed must be broken, and the opportunities provided by democracy must be given to Roma children so that they can participate as full citizens in the future of Europe" - Járóka demanded.
On behalf of the "European Year for Equal Opportunities" for all, the objective of the Summit for Equal Opportunities in Europe, organised every year since the Berlin Summit last year, is to ensure a single platform to support measures taken to promote equal opportunities and combat discrimination, targeted at European and Member State level.
