The elites in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the House of Representatives voting, contrary to the $700 billion bailout plan approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still is, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times of yesterday that confirms to us that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its quiet, moderate East Coast soul, favorable to federal institutions as well as to business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "the Washington ones" and the world of finance, powerful especially in the Central and Southern States.
The soul, precisely, which was despotically felt with the vote I was talking about at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is just one example of the changes, of the great changes that the current economic earthquake pre-announces or is already letting go: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and can be not just here.
In both the United States and Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena that have arisen for some time, so much so that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the update, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category State-sovereign, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which, obviously, have close relations with the foreigner, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of individuals and families who live in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for whom it is governed: that is to say, to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically, it is almost only here national.
Political internationalisation really seems out of hand, or it has little to say: the obvious proof is provided to us by the European Union, which, as usual, shares between the various interests and between the various national strategies, does not manage to decide any common political lines.
And so, it is from the government of each state that all expect interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a affection of credits: when we are going through a difficult period, there are only the states that possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources able to try to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two resources of invaluable value, elements that no market or international organization can ever dispose of in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the nation-state crisis is in perfect harmony with the ever-major importance that the more recent economic developments tend to attribute to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, indeed, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, of non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized at one stroke, that our future will have to settle its accounts more and more with things rather unmaterial such as water, crops, oil.
Things which can certainly be transported from one place to another from the earth, but which are absolutely linked to a confined space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly possesses more maps than he who is not, that is, he who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, foresees a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for someone who can take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shade.
And moreover, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even worrying: discredit, suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of remoteness that tends to involve the entire class of directors in an increasing number of Western countries.
Thus further increases the conviction of the various classes, before actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of majorities.
In short, The demand for leadership, feeds underground, a powerful and ramified movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifest themselves in the "revolts" of the improvised elections or, in the collective changes of the latter most recently, from the conservative rise in Austria Bavaria, the fall of the Labourers in Great Britain, the rebellion of the American Congressists against Bush (and it may well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not happen by chance).
We have the impression that traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, would say someone, have ever more difficulty, which is not of today's date, to understand and thus to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis strengthens, increases and potentially stirs up in a disproportionate way.
In view of all this, talking about a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda, seems frankly exaggerated.
But it is said that keeping eyes wide open is not without reason.
