Medications: never with fruit juices.
Attention to grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed mainly in the summer because they are de-altering and rich in vitamins, if combined with certain vital medicines, alter the absorption amplifying or decreasing, depending on the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices, whether canned or fresh, associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; during the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he launches a new alarm: a glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice is enough to reduce the absorption of certain vital drugs, cancelling their beneficial effects and putting patients at risk for their health.
Grapefruit juice has already been strongly criticized as being responsible for increasing the effects of certain anti-arrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-statinal and neurological drugs up to toxic levels.
MEDICINAL PRODUCTS IN RISK- It was the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which gave the news in a two-year newsletter, alerting doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger deriving from this mix and to pay attention to what one drinks, if one takes medicines such as, for example, Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT THAT PAMPLEMOUSSE- According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit drugs.
Long is the list of active substances inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
From there, the call of Michele Carruba, director of the pharmacology department of the Public University of Milan: "these discoveries are generally reported immediately to the various national and international drug agencies that will have to change the informative notes of the medicines if necessary.
It is always appropriate to read the illustrative papers of the medicines you are taking, and if something is not clear, not to be impressed, but to speak clearly to the doctor or pharmacist," stressed the expert to the Ansa agency.
