Student victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for one room.
The student rental market does not experience a crisis
According to Sunia's latest survey, the tenant union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euro in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding whole categories of young people, from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin must support- explains the head of the Sunia study office, Laura Mariani- in these cities, the high demand from students has so distorted the market that a process of generalized increase has even begun for residents.
In most cases, rental offers also involve a series of violations: free type contracts, unregistered, without rent limits, sub-leases.
For the Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of taxation are necessary to calm prices.
Reading in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, it ranges from 650 euros minimum (Zone Bande Nere), to an average value of 800 (Zone Lambiate, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Zone Vittoria)
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students concentrate in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and from 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in areas close to central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), about 600 euros are required for a single, 450 euros for a double bed.
Slightly lower values (€550 for a single) for areas close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can only save money if you move away in the peripheral areas: 300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a simple one, you spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the zones Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for bed, you have to count 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, where rentals are often taken by extra-community students, there is a further anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Farewell old cinema Paradiso, cities elect historic halls.
Historical cinemas close in favour of the Multiplex.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of the marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the periphery of the large multi-salles, and the death of the consumption of mono-salles in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable to us; it also has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historic places and charged with memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a bit of path and so many emotions", observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, film that offers to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of the jury of Cannes, and which told the poetry of a provincial hall, and the nostalgia of a way of living cinema, lost can be forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, mean everything: over the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the halls of the main cities that have paid mainly the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the areas most affected by the closure, Romaine Emilia leads with 82 single cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof which confirms that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is indeed the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-salle cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy over the last five years, 81 in Tuscany as in Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it would still be necessary to guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these frequentors are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the missed deliberation of the credit in favour of traders: the state's previous debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government is not complying with existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between 16 and 18 million euros per year.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city which, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation thanks to the signing of a protocol between Town Hall and Anec, the first of this kind in Italy, to defend and promote the cinemas single rooms of the historic centers and on the periphery.
Among the normative measures planned are tax facilities for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted area, and will have special parking rates and some parking lots.
"It is an initiative that I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna implementing other measures.
It is clear, however, that to contrast the super power of multiplexes, traditional rooms also need to improve the quality of sound and image, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Bagheria Supercinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" that I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have lived so much shared emotion, I turn on the other side so as not to see the signs blackened by dust.
